  

<h2 id="its-the-perfect-mix-of-simplicity-and-low-tech-plain-text-wizardry">It‚Äôs the perfect mix of simplicity and low-tech plain text wizardry</h2>
<p><a href="https://xenodium.com/journelly-for-ios" target="_blank">Journelly</a> is<span class="push-double"></span> <span class="pull-double">‚Äú</span>Like tweeting, but for your eyes only.‚Äù</p>
<p>It takes a very particular set of features for a new app to impress me enough to hit the purchase button as fast as I did with Journelly. Especially one with a hefty price tag and no free preview!</p>
<p>The $22.99 Australian dollar price tag feels more than fair when you consider that it‚Äôs a one-off: no subscriptions here.</p>
<p><em>If you‚Äôre interested in giving the app a serious run for its money before laying out that sort of cash, contact the developer on <a href="https://indieweb.social/@xenodium" target="_blank">Mastodon</a>,&nbsp;<a href="https://github.com/xenodium" target="_blank">Github</a>,&nbsp;<a href="https://twitter.com/xenodium" target="_blank">Twitter</a>, or&nbsp;<a href="https://uk.linkedin.com/in/xenodium" target="_blank">Linkedin</a> to request a spot in the TestFlight group.</em></p>
<p><em>Once you‚Äôve determined the app is a good fit for you please do support further development by purchasing it on the App Store and leaving an honest review. It‚Äôs fairly effortless to switch between App Store and Test Flight versions.</em></p>
<p><img src="https://cdn.blot.im/blog_177bc256f0ee469c998e912e20ece048/_image_cache/1ea2b9be-4291-4dcd-8f72-4a3e7c628413.png" alt="Screenshot of three iPhone screens: two standard Journelly entries with a bread recipe and a quote, plus an iPhone home screen showing Calendar, Clock, and a Beorg widget, with the Calendar, Workflowy, Journelly, and Obsidian icons in the dock" width="2336" height="1678"></p>
<p><em>Drafts has been retired from pride of place on my iPhone dock ‚Äî never thought I‚Äôd see the day</em></p>
<hr>
<h3 id="stealth-org">Stealth Org <span class="small-caps">üï∂Ô∏è</span></h3>
<p>Journelly is the first Org-powered app I‚Äôve seen that lays out the welcome mat for people who don‚Äôt even know what Org is, never mind how to use it.</p>
<p>I recognise the power that Org can bring to my darling plain text, but I‚Äôm not ready to fall down the Org/Emacs rabbit hole.</p>
<p>A steep learning curve (plus a healthy fear of getting in too deep) has always been the largest barrier between me and anything resembling Org ‚Äî until now.</p>
<p><img src="https://cdn.blot.im/blog_177bc256f0ee469c998e912e20ece048/_image_cache/a5b9e738-e923-4857-963c-b05b7a3de48d.png" alt="Screenshots of Journelly in source mode on iPhone and on Mac" width="1608" height="1140"> <em>Org-ignorant people can read the markup, because it actually makes sense ‚Äî how cool!</em></p>
<hr>
<h3 id="journelly-stores-entries-locally-in-plain-text">Journelly stores entries locally in plain text!!</h3>
<p>At its simplest Org is human readable plain text, specially formatted so that apps like Emacs can do wonderful things with it. Fortunately, Journelly users don‚Äôt need to know anything about Org. And that is what excites me the most, because I know next to nothing about it!</p>
<p>Download the app, open the app, press the prominent blue <code>+</code>, and start typing. That‚Äôs what I call a low entry barrier to something built on a powerful geek-fueled engine.</p>
<p>Settings in Journelly let you choose between keeping your notes completely local, or syncing via iCloud (officially supported) or other cloud services (at your own risk).</p>
<h3 id="accessing-the-journelly-files-on-a-mac">Accessing the Journelly files on a Mac</h3>
<p>I recommend turning on iCloud storage so you can access your notes on your Mac. Control-click the Journelly folder to choose the Keep Downloaded option. It‚Äôs also a good idea to regularly export a zipped archive to another (version controlled) backup space.</p>
<p>You can format text in Journelly posts to be <code>*bold*</code>, <code>/italic/</code>, <code>_underline_</code>, <code>+strike-through+</code>, <code>=verbatim=</code>, or <code>~code~</code>. I‚Äôve noticed that you can‚Äôt begin a new line with bold formatted text as it returns the error<span class="push-double"></span> <span class="pull-double">‚Äú</span>Org sub-headings are not currently supported‚Äù.</p>
<p>A Keyboard Maestro shortcut quickly opens my Journelly file when I‚Äôm on my laptop. From there I can add new entries and easily copy paste existing entries to other locations.</p>
<p><strong>Hot tip</strong>: To keep sync working well, close the Journelly.org file on your Mac when not actively editing it there.</p>
<h3 id="journelly-features-id-like-to-see">Journelly features I‚Äôd like to see</h3>
<p>Journelly is still a very young app. It‚Äôs under active development by √Ålvaro R. of Xenodium, who created it for his own use and has stated that at least some of the features I would like to see are already on his radar.</p>
<p>Here‚Äôs what Journelly can‚Äôt currently do, that I wish it could:</p>
<ul>
<li>Show a tag picker (now available!)</li>
<li>Show (and allow navigation by) outline: years, months, weeks, days - or at least have an easy way (like double tapping on the Journelly title bar) to zip back up to the most recent entry, because dragging the scroll bar is awkward</li>
<li>Search for<span class="push-double"></span> <span class="pull-double">‚Äú</span>exact strings‚Äù (when I search for <span class="small-caps">TODO</span> I don‚Äôt want it to match Mas<strong>todo</strong>n)</li>
<li>Search by any combination of date, location, weather, and posts with images</li>
<li>Allow selection and copying of text without going into Edit or Markup modes</li>
<li>Paste images from the clipboard (now available!)</li>
<li>Markdown support</li>
<li>Subheads and indented, foldable text within posts (coming with Markdown support?)</li>
<li>Search and edit in Markup view</li>
<li><span class="small-caps">PDF</span> export to include images</li>
<li>Image names to begin with the date they were added in <span class="small-caps">YYYYMMDD</span> format</li>
<li>Audio files in posts</li>
</ul>
<p>Journelly may soon be compatible with Markdown, yay! If that is something you would like to see, √Ålvaro invites you to <a href="https://xenodium.com/journelly-for-ios#:~:text=Please%20register%20your%20interest" target="_blank">register your interest</a>. The more requests he gets, the sooner Markdown support will come.</p>
<h3 id="no-journelly-wont-be-my-obtfs-new-home">No, Journelly won‚Äôt be my <span class="small-caps">OBTF</span><span class="push-single"></span><span class="pull-single">‚Äô</span>s new home</h3>
<p>Ten days in with this app and I‚Äôm (joyfully) adding multiple daily entries. It‚Äôs similar to ‚Äî but not the same as ‚Äî the way I add notes to my <a href="https://ellanew.com/2025-04-14-obtf-start-here" title="wikilink">One Big Text File</a> (<span class="small-caps">OBTF</span>) and will no doubt shape the way I use it.</p>
<p>Prediction: <span class="small-caps">OBTF</span> continues to live in Obsidian and be my home base and starting point for longer form notes, while Journelly takes over as a low-friction space for personal journal entries. The two exist in parallel. (There are probably ways to feed one into the other, but I can‚Äôt see any reason to do that.)</p>
<p>I‚Äôm certainly enjoying journalling more (and actually <em>doing</em> it) now that it‚Äôs so quick and easy to access. And I‚Äôm not alone, though most of the positive reviews I‚Äôve seen thus far are by people already well versed in the world of Emacs. I suspect that a trial period or freemium offer might tip the balance for more org-ignorant people to give Journelly a go.</p>
<h3 id="the-way-i-use-obsidian-discourages-smaller-thoughts">The way I use Obsidian discourages smaller thoughts</h3>
<p>Obsidian does the job but it‚Äôs significantly slower than Journelly to start up and get to where I want to be. That friction makes me less likely to record small thoughts.</p>
<p>Drafts used to solve that problem but for several interconnected, sync-related reasons, I found it was no longer the best way to add to Obsidian files on my mobile devices. See last week‚Äôs <a href="https://ellanew.com/ptpl/156-2025-05-12-leaving-obsidian-remember-insurance" title="wikilink"><span class="small-caps">PTPL</span></a> on the restrictions of using Obsidian Sync with a vault stored in Dropbox.</p>
<p>While Shortcuts might work as a quick entry point to Obsidian, I have to say there‚Äôs something very very nice about a one-trick pony that speaks my language. There‚Äôs also a high distraction risk with Obsidian that Journelly doesn‚Äôt have.</p>
<h3 id="high-praise-for-journelly-and-another-promising-org-app">High praise for Journelly, and another promising Org app</h3>
<p>The Journelly app icon has already earned a place with the Blessed Four that appear on the dock of my iPhone screen. High praise indeed! Journelly deserves a solid 8 out of 10, and I look forward to seeing it get even better.</p>
<p>Next step in my journey to playing with Org without actually learning it, or opening Emacs: Beorg for task management. It‚Äôs going well so far, looking very much like it will replace todo.txt.</p>
